Gnostic roots. Drawing from J. G. Frazer, who studied ancient nature cults that associated the physical condition of the king with the productivity of the land, Weston considers how the legend of the Grail related to fertility rites--with the lance and the cup serving as sexual symbols. She traces its origins to a Gnostic text that served as a link between ancient vegetation cults and the Celts and Christians who embellished the story. Conceiving of the Grail saga as a literary outgrowth of ancient ritual, she seeks a Gnostic Christian interpretation that unites the quest for fertility with the striving for mystical oneness with God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGrailxLegendsxHistory and criticism. 0aRomancesxHistory and criticism. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAdonis.  aArthur.  aAttis.  aBleheris (version of Grail Story).  aBorron, Robert de.  aCardoil.  aCumont, M. F.  aDead Knight (in Grail romances).  aEisler, Dr R.  aElucidation.  aEniautos-Daimon.  aFisher King.  aFrazer, Sir J. G.  aGawain.  aGiraldus Cambrensis.  aGrand Saint Graal.  aHarrison, Miss J. E.  aHippolytus, Bishop.  aIndra.  aJoseph of Arimathea.  aKorybantes.  aKouretes.  aLancelot (prose).  aMagna Mater, The.  aMannhardt, W.  aMaruts.  aMithra.  aMumming Plays.  aNaassenes.  aNitze, Dr W. A.  aOsiris.  aParzival.  aPerceval.  aPerlesvaus.  aQueste.  aSone de Nansai.  aTarot.1 aSegal, Robert A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691217741zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691217741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97806912